article.description: Shawn Marion scored 18 of his season-high 32 points in the second half and Phoenix used a surge over the final five minutes to pull away from the Memphis Grizzlies, 98-85.
article.headline: Marion scores 13 of his 32 in fourth quarter
article.linkText: Suns ride red-hot Marion past Grizzlies in fourth
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Shawn Marion was on a roll, and the Phoenix Suns rode him to victory Wednesday night.
Marion

Marion scored 13 of his season-high 32 points in the fourth quarter, sparking the Suns over the Memphis Grizzlies 98-85. It was Marion's second big game in a row, following a 30-point performance against Miami on Monday night. Marion recovered from a shaky start in which he missed his first five shots, hitting 12 of his next 16. He also was perfect from the foul line, going 6-for-6, and grabbed 12 rebounds in recording his fifth straight double-double. "I'm just playing an emotional game,'' Marion said. "I'm taking the shots when they present themselves. I wasn't doing that before. I'm trying not to force the issue. Both coaches agreed that Marion was the difference. "He had a huge game,'' Phoenix's Frank Johnson said. Memphis' Hubie Brown said, "Down the stretch, I thought Shawn Marion was great. He made a lot (of shots) ... big ones, with the clock running down, which we didn't get.'' "He's a rhythm shooter and he got hot,'' the Grizzlies' Shane Battier said of Marion. "He had a bounce in his step. He's got a huge contract. I think he's worth every penny of it.'' Stephon Marbury added 20 points for the Suns, who ended a two-game losing skid, and rookie Amare Stoudemire had 14 points and a season-high 15 rebounds. Brown was very impressed by the 20-year-old Stoudemire. "The young man is going to be terrific,'' he said. "With him, the offense is a bonus. How about the 15 boards and the six offensive rebounds? This is what he's all about. He's all about effort, young legs and great jumping ability. He's a real diamond for them.'' Rookie Gordan Giricek had 18 points for Memphis, which is 0-9 on the road and 2-17 overall. Rookie Drew Gooden scored 12 and Lorenzen Wright and Mike Batiste had 11 apiece for Memphis, which lost its fourth in a row. Pau Gasol, the Grizzlies' leading scorer, was held to nine. Phoenix pulled away to its biggest victory of the season in the final 4:43. The Suns led 83-81 before Penny Hardaway's two free throws started a game-ending 15-4 run. With Marbury scoring 15 points and Marion collecting 13, the Suns matched their season best for the first half with 49 points and held a six-point lead. Giricek had 12 points in the first quarter when Memphis built a 25-19 lead, but he failed to score another point before halftime. Giricek's second 3-pointer in the opening period gave the Grizzlies their biggest lead of the game, 25-15. But the Suns capitalized on their fast-moving offense in the second period and outscored Memphis 30-18. The Grizzlies regained the lead briefly in the third quarter, 65-64, on a short turnaround jumper by Wright. But the Suns came right back, outscoring Memphis 9-3 the rest of the period and led 73-68 going into the final 12 minutes. In the fourth quarter, Phoenix did not have a turnover, while Memphis had three.

Game notes
Brevin Knight, second on the Grizzlies in assists (4.0), missed his ninth game in the last 12 with a sprained right ankle. ... Suns forward Tom Gugliotta sat out his seventh straight game with a contusion of the right foot. He also sustained a bruised hand in an automobile accident Tuesday, but that is not considered serious. ... Phoenix center Jake Tsakalidis is eligible to come off the disabled list Friday against the Indiana Pacers after missing five games with a bulging disc in his spine. ... These teams meet again Sunday at the Pyramid in Memphis. ... The Grizzlies ended a nine-game losing streak at Phoenix by beating the Suns 102-96 last Jan. 10.
